You can define a `TreeView` in UWP XAML like this, as detailed [here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/design/controls-and-patterns/tree-view):

```xaml
&lt;TreeView ItemsSource=&quot;{x:Bind ListOfStudents}&quot;&gt;
    &lt;TreeView.ItemTemplate&gt;
        &lt;DataTemplate x:DataType=&quot;model:Student&quot;&gt;
            &lt;TreeViewItem ItemsSource=&quot;{x:Bind homeworks}&quot;
                          Content=&quot;{x:Bind Name}&quot;/&gt;
        &lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
    &lt;/TreeView.ItemTemplate&gt;
&lt;/TreeView&gt;
```

You would then need to define a `DataTemplate` for each of class you expect to display. Add this in your `TreeView` XAML:
```xaml
&lt;TreeView.Resources&gt;
	&lt;DataTemplate x:DataType=&quot;model:ScienceH&quot;&gt;
		&lt;StackPanel Orientation=&quot;Horizontal&quot;&gt;
			&lt;TextBlock Text=&quot;{Binding Date}&quot; /&gt;
			&lt;TextBlock Text=&quot;{Binding Vote}&quot; /&gt;
		&lt;/StackPanel&gt;
	&lt;/DataTemplate&gt;

	&lt;DataTemplate x:DataType=&quot;model:PhysicsH &quot;&gt;
		&lt;StackPanel Orientation=&quot;Horizontal&quot;&gt;
			&lt;TextBlock Text=&quot;{Binding Date}&quot; /&gt;
			&lt;TextBlock Text=&quot;{Binding Vote}&quot; /&gt;
			&lt;TextBlock Text=&quot;{Binding Points}&quot; /&gt;
		&lt;/StackPanel&gt;
	&lt;/DataTemplate&gt;
&lt;/TreeView.Resources&gt;
```

You can also read more on the `DataTemplate` class [here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/uwp/api/windows.ui.xaml.datatemplate).

Note that, as suggested in the comments, you need to implement change notifications in your classes to ensure correct binding. This is all detailed [here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/uwp/data-binding/data-binding-in-depth).

Alternatively, you seem to have a `TreeView` with a tree structure of known, fixed depth: depth 0 would be the list of `Student` and depth 1 would be the list of `Homework`, so you could also do without `TreeView` and simply nest two `ItemsControl` within one another.

